A Future Beyond Measure
JERUSALEM – At almost 90 years of age, I can recall no time when the past was considered so insignificant in political decision-making.
None of the significant developments of the present were foreseen by anyone.
Experts did study the past, but due to their confinement within old paradigms, they were unable to deduce the future from it.
Given the dynamic complexity of the world today, where even more events are interdependent due to a rapidly changing, science-based world economy, we fail to predict the future on the basis of a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is declining. In the globalized economy of today, it is not politicians but innovators who have the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome, because science and technology are boundless.
Global acting companies want to conduct their businesses all over the world, which, on the one hand, harms sovereignty, but on the other hand, weakens racism and prejudices as well as nationalism in a significant way.
Due to this change, the fate of this world is now in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically savvy than their parents and are connected to each other through social networks that transcend national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people are also at the forefront of forming emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia, mark no battle of cultures, but a clash of generations.
The young generation knows that the way in which states and economies are currently led is not suitable for the new times.
However, there are political "free riders" who want to exploit this latest awakening. But not through the further development of an agenda of freedom, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, Islamist extremists are primarily appropriating the protests of the young generation and thus stealing the revolution from them.
Israel has responded positively to the will of the young generation, but cannot and should not intervene in the events of the Arab world.
We are at heart with the rebellious youths and their legitimate desire for freedom and basic rights, which should enable them to be heard, choose their political leadership, and earn their living.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, for the existence as an island of prosperity in the midst of a sea of poverty is unnatural.
However, there is serious concern that the politically well-organized extremists will try to win control over less well-organized liberals in elections and thus prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists can offer no real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
Current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which also includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of traditional authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example for others when it comes to gaining economic prosperity and social freedom, because its success lies in the fact that the country initially had absolutely nothing.
On our return to our homeland, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. For this reason, we have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita today.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We consume less water and yet have higher crop yields per square meter of cultivation area than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also accomplish.
We are glad to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Above all, we must do everything within our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to dominate another people, and that's not Israel's purpose either.
We are genuinely interested in creating a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because resolving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing the extremists who are intent on manipulating the citizen movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by offering incentives to countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and groundbreaking political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Especially Iran is a source of moral decay, where extremism is promoted and reforms are blocked. Legitimate protests of its own citizens are being smashed and they work against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
Furthermore, Iran uses several proxies to instigate terror against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, Lebanon, and Iraq.
It is possible that Iran acquiring atomic weapons could shake the Middle East and further fuel extremism and violence, if the country's leaders succeed in doing so.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But Israel is not the only one under threat. Iran poses a danger to peace and stability worldwide.
The democracies of this world have declared that they will not allow Iran to obtain atomic weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it is too late.
Going beyond these short-term challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to deal with the world of today.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education should provide all children with the opportunity to exploit their potential.
The teachers of today should motivate our children to creativity and innovation.
Self-actualization is just as important as free expression of opinion.
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
In fact: experience is overvalued and frequently limits the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back makes no sense.
